[start section id="20102"]

Metastatic cecal cancer, KRAS mutated.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Wheeler is a very pleasant 53-year-old patient from 88581 Augusta, who is being referred to Macdonald Care Center to obtain opinion regarding the future management of his disease.
On October 8, 2009, he underwent a screening colonoscopy during which a cecal mass was found.  Biopsy confirmed the presence of a grade 3 (out of 4) adenocarcinoma.  Pathology was reviewed here at Macdonald Care Center.  It is of note that a KRAS status was obtained, and the tumor was classified as KRAS mutated.
On the same-day, a CT-scan without contrast due to prior contrast allergy was performed which revealed two intrahepatic lesions.  Subsequent PET CT-scan on October 13, 2009, revealed about three areas of tracer uptake in the liver.
Subsequently the patient started systemic chemotherapy with FOLFOX plus bevacizumab.  He received six cycles from October to December 31, 2009.  Intent of this chemotherapy was neoadjuvant mainly with the eventual goal to resect primary tumor and metastasis.  It is of note that the tumor marker CEA decreased from 78 to 8 on therapy.  The patient tolerated the treatment very well except for cold sensitivities and fatigue.
A PET scan on January 4, 2010, showed complete resolution of the intrahepatic lesions.  It did not show any tracer uptake anymore.  His surgeon, Dr. Munson, then contacted Dr. Rutland at Macdonald Care Center to see if the situation of disappearing liver metastasis surgical quote was still warranted.  Eventually the patient was referred to Macdonald Care Center for further discussions about the best therapeutic course here.
Upon presentation here, Mr. Wheeler says that he did not have any tumor or treatment-related symptoms anymore.  His sensory neuropathy has completely resolved.  He feels energetic, has no pain, no fever, and no chills.

[end section id="20103"]

